<li id="cite_note-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web"><a href="http://www.bipm.org/fr/CGPM/db/17/1/" class="external text" title="http://www.bipm.org/fr/CGPM/db/17/1/" rel="nofollow">"<span lang="fr" xml:lang="fr">Définition du mètre</span>"</a>. written at Sèvres (in French). <i><span lang="fr" xml:lang="fr">Résolution 1 de la 17<sup>e</sup> réunion de la CGPM</span></i>. <a href="/wiki/Bureau_International_des_Poids_et_Mesures" title="Bureau International des Poids et Mesures" class="mw-redirect">Bureau International des Poids et Mesures</a>. 1983<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.bipm.org/fr/CGPM/db/17/1/" class="external free" title="http://www.bipm.org/fr/CGPM/db/17/1/" rel="nofollow">http://www.bipm.org/fr/CGPM/db/17/1/</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2008-10-03</span>.  "<span lang="fr" xml:lang="fr">Le mètre est la longueur du trajet parcouru dans le vide par la lumière pendant une durée de <span style="white-space:nowrap;">1/299 792 458</span> de seconde.</span>"</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=%3Cspan+lang%3D%22fr%22+xml%3Alang%3D%22fr%22%3ED%C3%A9finition+du+m%C3%A8tre%3C%2Fspan%3E%5B%5BCategory%3AArticles+containing+French+language+text%5D%5D&amp;rft.atitle=%3Cspan+lang%3D%22fr%22+xml%3Alang%3D%22fr%22%3ER%26eacute%3Bsolution+1+de+la+17%3Csup%3Ee%3C%2Fsup%3E+r%26eacute%3Bunion+de+la+CGPM%3C%2Fspan%3E%5B%5BCategory%3AArticles+containing+French+language+text%5D%5D&amp;rft.date=1983&amp;rft.pub=%5B%5BBureau+International+des+Poids+et+Mesures%5D%5D&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.bipm.org%2Ffr%2FCGPM%2Fdb%2F17%2F1%2F&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Introduction_to_special_relativity"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span> English translation: <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web"><a href="http://www.bipm.org/en/CGPM/db/17/1/" class="external text" title="http://www.bipm.org/en/CGPM/db/17/1/" rel="nofollow">"Definition of the metre"</a>. <i>Resolution 1 of the 17th meeting of the CGPM</i><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.bipm.org/en/CGPM/db/17/1/" class="external free" title="http://www.bipm.org/en/CGPM/db/17/1/" rel="nofollow">http://www.bipm.org/en/CGPM/db/17/1/</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2008-10-03</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Definition+of+the+metre&amp;rft.atitle=Resolution+1+of+the+17th+meeting+of+the+CGPM&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.bipm.org%2Fen%2FCGPM%2Fdb%2F17%2F1%2F&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Introduction_to_special_relativity"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-3"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREFTom_Roberts_and_Siegmar_Schleif2007">Tom Roberts and Siegmar Schleif (October 2007). <a href="http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/physics/Relativity/SR/experiments.html" class="external text" title="http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/physics/Relativity/SR/experiments.html" rel="nofollow">"What is the experimental basis of Special Relativity?"</a>. <i>Usenet Physics FAQ</i><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/physics/Relativity/SR/experiments.html" class="external free" title="http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/physics/Relativity/SR/experiments.html" rel="nofollow">http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/physics/Relativity/SR/experiments.html</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2008-09-17</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=What+is+the+experimental+basis+of+Special+Relativity%3F&amp;rft.atitle=Usenet+Physics+FAQ&amp;rft.aulast=Tom+Roberts+and+Siegmar+Schleif&amp;rft.au=Tom+Roberts+and+Siegmar+Schleif&amp;rft.date=October+2007&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fmath.ucr.edu%2Fhome%2Fbaez%2Fphysics%2FRelativity%2FSR%2Fexperiments.html&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Introduction_to_special_relativity"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-4"><b><a href="#cite_ref-4" title="">^</a></b> <a href="/wiki/Hermann_Minkowski" title="Hermann Minkowski">Hermann Minkowski</a>, <a href="http://de.wikisource.org/wiki/Raum_und_Zeit_(Minkowski)" class="external text" title="http://de.wikisource.org/wiki/Raum_und_Zeit_(Minkowski)" rel="nofollow">"Raum und Zeit"</a>, 80. Versammlung Deutscher Naturforscher (Köln, 1908). Published in Physikalische Zeitschrift <b>10</b> 104-111 (1909) and Jahresbericht der Deutschen Mathematiker-Vereinigung <b>18</b> 75-88 (1909). For an English translation, see Lorentz et al. (1952).</li>
<li id="cite_note-6"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6" title="">^</a></b> Walter, S.(1999) The non-Euclidean style of Minkowskian relativity. The Symbolic Universe, J. Gray (ed.), Oxford University Press, 1999 <a href="http://www.univ-nancy2.fr/DepPhilo/walter/papers/nes.pdf" class="external free" title="http://www.univ-nancy2.fr/DepPhilo/walter/papers/nes.pdf" rel="nofollow">http://www.univ-nancy2.fr/DepPhilo/walter/papers/nes.pdf</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-8"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFEinstein"><a href="/wiki/Albert_Einstein" title="Albert Einstein">Einstein, Albert</a>. "Appendix 5: Relativity and the Problem of Space". <i>Relativity. The special and general theory.</i>. Translation by Lawson, R.W.. London: Routledge classics 2001. pp.&#160;p. 152.  "It appears therefore more natural to think of physical reality as a four dimensional existence, instead of, as hitherto, the <i>evolution</i> of a three dimensional existence."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Appendix+5%3A+Relativity+and+the+Problem+of+Space&amp;rft.atitle=Relativity.+The+special+and+general+theory.&amp;rft.aulast=Einstein&amp;rft.aufirst=Albert&amp;rft.au=Einstein%2C+Albert&amp;rft.pages=pp.%26nbsp%3Bp.+152&amp;rft.place=London&amp;rft.pub=Routledge+classics+2001&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Introduction_to_special_relativity"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-9"><b><a href="#cite_ref-9" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFPenrose"><a href="/wiki/Roger_Penrose" title="Roger Penrose">Penrose, Roger</a>. "Introduction". in <a href="/wiki/Richard_Feynman" title="Richard Feynman">Richard Feynman</a>. <i>Six Not-So-Easy Pieces</i> (Penguin Books ed.). England.  "The idea that the history of the universe should be viewed, physically, as a <i>four</i>-dimensional spacetime, rather than as a three dimensional space evolving with time is indeed fundamental to modern physics."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Introduction&amp;rft.atitle=Six+Not-So-Easy+Pieces&amp;rft.aulast=Penrose&amp;rft.aufirst=Roger&amp;rft.au=Penrose%2C+Roger&amp;rft.edition=Penguin+Books&amp;rft.place=England&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Introduction_to_special_relativity"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-10"><b><a href="#cite_ref-10" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFWeyl1918">Weyl, Hermann (1918). <i>Space, time, matter.</i>. New York: Dover Books edition 1952.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Space%2C+time%2C+matter.&amp;rft.aulast=Weyl&amp;rft.aufirst=Hermann&amp;rft.au=Weyl%2C+Hermann&amp;rft.date=1918&amp;rft.place=New+York&amp;rft.pub=Dover+Books+edition+1952&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Introduction_to_special_relativity"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span>: "The adequate mathematical formulation of Einstein's discovery was first given by Minkowski: to him we are indebted for the idea of four dimensional world-geometry, on which we based our argument from the outset."</li>
<li id="cite_note-11"><b><a href="#cite_ref-11" title="">^</a></b> Kip Thorne and Roger Blandford in their <a href="http://www.pma.caltech.edu/Courses/ph136/yr2004/0401.1.K.pdf" class="external text" title="http://www.pma.caltech.edu/Courses/ph136/yr2004/0401.1.K.pdf" rel="nofollow">Caltec physics notes</a> say: "Special relativity is the limit of general relativity in the complete absence of gravity; its arena is flat, 4-dimensional Minkowski spacetime."</li>
<li id="cite_note-12"><b><a href="#cite_ref-12" title="">^</a></b> Sean Carroll <a href="http://www.pma.caltech.edu/Courses/ph136/yr2004/0401.1.K.pdf" class="external text" title="http://www.pma.caltech.edu/Courses/ph136/yr2004/0401.1.K.pdf" rel="nofollow">says</a>: "..it makes sense to think of SR as a theory of 4-dimensional spacetime, known as Minkowski space."</li>
<li id="cite_note-Einstein2-13"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Einstein2_13-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFEinstein1916">Einstein, A. (1916). <i>Relativity. The special and general theory.</i>. Tr. Lawson, R.W.. London: Routledge classics 2001.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Relativity.+The+special+and+general+theory.&amp;rft.aulast=Einstein&amp;rft.aufirst=A.&amp;rft.au=Einstein%2C+A.&amp;rft.date=1916&amp;rft.place=London&amp;rft.pub=Routledge+classics+2001&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Introduction_to_special_relativity"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
</ol>
